translations = {
    "tej": "18.2 Sri Bhagavan said -- Some wise men (scholars) understand the renunciation of desire-motivated actions as \"Sannyasa\", and thoughtful people call the abandonment of the fruits of all actions as \"Tyaga\".",
    
    "chinmay": "Hindi Commentary By Swami Chinmayananda 18.2 Renunciation of desire-motivated actions is called Sannyasa, and the abandonment of the fruits of all actions is called Tyaga. Those who are ignorant of scriptural principles do not perceive any difference between the two, because desire is always for obtaining a result. Therefore, renunciation of desire-driven actions and abandonment of attachment to the fruits of actions seem identical. This could be due to ignorance of the scriptures or their superficial study. There is no doubt that both mean the renunciation of desire, but there is some difference between Tyaga and Sannyasa. Nevertheless, Tyaga is an inseparable part of Sannyasa. A person performs actions in the present and hopes to get the desired result in the future. The outcome of present action is the future fruit. Therefore, desireless action can only happen in the present, whereas the anxiety of the mind arising from worry about enjoying the fruits belongs to the future. The culmination of present action lies in the future fruit. Desire and distraction cause unrest in the mind. The more intense the desire, the greater will be the loss of our inner powers, and such a powerless person cannot perform any action with skill and enthusiasm. It is also noteworthy that it is the ego or the individual soul that desires. Therefore, the cessation of the ego means the cessation of the individual self and the steady establishment of the seeker in their supreme nature. Actions are performed in the present and their results are expected in the future. A person who worries about the fruit loses their capacity to act in the present. Naturally, the probability of that person getting the desired result decreases, because the fruit of action depends on the effort of the doer and many other factors like the laws of nature. Therefore, we are instructed to renounce attachment to the fruits of action. In brief, it can be said that Tyaga is the means and Sannyasa is the goal. The practice of Tyaga and Sannyasa is related to our actions. Lord Krishna never tires of emphasizing the importance of action. Neither of these two words indicates that we should neglect action. On the contrary, both insist on the performance of action. We must perform actions. However, these actions must be free from egoism, selfishness, and attachment to fruits. Attachment to fruits acts as an obstacle to our efficiency. In the absence of attachment to fruits, our actions can yield their full reward. We can say that the definitions of these two words given in the Gita are more liberal and accommodating than their meanings used in the Vedas. On whether an ignorant person should perform actions or not, it is said:",
    
    "madhav": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Madhavacharya 18.2 Sannyasa is the renunciation of desire-prompted actions, either by performing them without desiring the fruits, or by non-performance. Tyaga, however, is indeed the abandonment of fruits. Thus says the Prachinashala Sruti: 'Renunciation (nyasa) is the abandonment of desire-prompted actions either without desire or by non-performance; whereas abandonment of the fruits is Tyaga.'",
    
    "anand": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Anandgiri 18.2 Objection: Since Sannyasa and Tyaga have been mentioned in various places in the previous chapters, why are they being asked about again? Since it is not proper to ask about what is already known, [the commentator] says 'tatra tatra' (in those various places). The meaning is that their meanings were not fully extracted, not fully explained, and not clearly distinguished. Since the question arose from a desire to know, the Lord, understanding the questioner's intent through the question, gave the reply; thus [the commentator] says 'atah' (therefore). By presenting two views, He explains the difference in meaning between the words Sannyasa and Tyaga, in the verse beginning with 'kamyanam'.\nObjection: In that case, are the words Sannyasa and Tyaga entirely different in meaning? If so, it would contradict common usage.\nAnticipating this, [the commentator] says 'yadi' (if), indicating that although there is an internal distinction, there is no absolute difference.\nObjection: Since the daily obligatory (nitya) and occasional (naimittika) duties are fruitless, it is impossible to renounce their fruits—just as a barren woman cannot give up a son. Therefore, the stated meaning of the word Tyaga cannot be established.\nAnswer: 'naisha doshah' (this defect does not arise). Since the Lord desires that even the daily obligatory duties have results, it is possible to renounce their fruits, and the stated meaning of Tyaga is valid.\n[The commentator] supports this view that the Lord intends them to have results by pointing to the remaining part of the text, saying 'vakshyati' (He will say).\nObjection: If so, then the fruit would accrue equally to both the Sannyasins and non-Sannyasins who perform the daily obligatory and other duties.\nAnswer: 'na eva' (certainly not), says [the commentator]. The word 'cha' (and) has the force of drawing in 'vakshyati'. Summarizing and recalling the meaning of the spoken words in relation to the context, [the commentator] says 'sannyasinam' (to the Sannyasins).",
    
    "rams": "Hindi Translation By Swami Ramsukhdas 18.2 Sri Bhagavan said -- Some wise men say that the renunciation of desire-prompted actions is Sannyasa, and some other wise men say that the abandonment of the fruits of all actions is Tyaga. Some wise men say that actions should be abandoned as an evil, while other wise men say that actions of sacrifice, charity, and austerity should not be abandoned.\n\nHindi Commentary By Swami Ramsukhdas 18.2 Commentary -- There are four views held by philosophical scholars:\n1 -- kamyanam karmanam nyasam sannyasam kavayo viduh -- Some scholars say that the renunciation of desire-prompted actions is called Sannyasa; i.e., giving up those actions which are performed for the attainment of the desirable and the avoidance of the undesirable is Sannyasa.\n2 -- sarvakarmaphalatyagam prahustyagam vicaksanah -- Some scholars say that renouncing the desire for the fruits of all actions is called Tyaga; i.e., performing one's duties without desiring any fruit is Tyaga.\n3 -- tyajyam dosa vadityeke karma prahurmanisinah -- Some scholars say that all actions should be abandoned as an evil.\n4 -- yajnadanatapahkarma na tyajyamiti capare -- Other scholars say that even if one renounces all other actions, actions of sacrifice, charity, and austerity should not be abandoned.\n\nIn the above four views, two divisions are visible -- the first and third views belong to Sannyasa (Sankhyayoga), while the second and fourth views belong to Tyaga (Karmayoga). Even within these two divisions, there are slight differences. In the first view, there is only the renunciation of desire-prompted actions, whereas in the third view, there is the renunciation of all action. Similarly, in the second view, there is the abandonment of the fruits of actions, whereas in the fourth view, the abandonment of actions of sacrifice, charity, and austerity is forbidden.\n\nThe shortcomings of the four views of the philosophers and the unique features of the Lord's view in comparison to them are discussed as follows:\n1 -- kamyanam karmanam nyasam sannyasam -- In this first view of Sannyasa, only the renunciation of desire-prompted actions is mentioned, but besides these, daily obligatory (nitya) and occasional (naimittika) duties still remain. Therefore, this view is not complete, because it neither mentions the renunciation of the sense of doership (kartritva) nor establishment in the self (svarupa). However, in the Lord's view, the egoistic sense of doership does not remain, and one is established in the self; as in the seventeenth verse of this chapter, where the abandonment of the sense of doership is shown by saying \"he who is free from the egoistic notion and whose intellect is not tainted,\" and establishment in the self is shown by saying \"even if he kills these people, he does not kill, nor is he bound.\"\n2 -- tyajyam dosavadityeke -- In this second view of Sannyasa, there is the abandonment of all actions like an evil. But no one can abandon all actions completely (Gita 3.5), and maintenance of life is not possible by abandoning all actions (Gita 3.8). Therefore, the Lord has declared the abandonment of obligatory duties out of delusion to be Tamasika (Gita 18.7, 18.8).\n3 -- sarvakarmaphalatyagam -- In this first view of Tyaga, only the abandonment of fruits is mentioned. Here, the abandonment of fruits refers only to the abandonment of desire. The abandonment of attachment and possessiveness cannot be included under this; because if we do so, there will be no difference between the views of the philosophers and the Lord. In the Lord's view, both attachment to action and attachment to fruits are to be abandoned -- \"renouncing attachment and fruits\" (Gita 18.6).\n4 -- yajnadanatapahkarma na tyajyam -- In this second view of Tyaga, i.e., Karmayoga, it is said that actions of sacrifice, charity, and austerity should not be abandoned. But nothing is said about performing or not performing other duties relating to one's class (varna), stage of life (ashrama), circumstances, etc. -- this is its incompleteness. In the Lord's view, these actions should not only be not abandoned, but if they are not being done, they must be done, and in addition, actions like pilgrimage, fasting, etc., should also be performed by abandoning fruits and attachment (Gita 18.5, 18.6).\n\nConnection -- After showing the four views of the philosophers in the preceding verses, the Lord now states His own view regarding Tyaga in the next three verses.",
    
    "jaya": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Jayatritha 18.2 Some explain the verse 'kamyanam karmanam...' as follows: 'The renunciation of desire-prompted actions like the Ashvamedha in their physical form is Sannyasa, and the abandonment of the fruits of all actions, including the daily obligatory and occasional ones, is Tyaga.' Keeping in mind that this view is incorrect, [the commentator] says 'phala...' (fruit...). For optional desire-prompted actions, Sannyasa means their abandonment by giving up the qualifying desire for fruits like heaven; for mandatory desire-prompted actions, it means abandonment by not performing them physically. Tyaga, on the other hand, is the abandonment of the fruits of desire-prompted actions alone, and whether they are performed or not is not intended here. Why is this so? To this [the commentator] says 'tatha hi...' (indeed...). Because seekers of liberation, like Janaka and Ashvapati, performed actions like the Ashvamedha without desiring their results, and not by physically abandoning desire-prompted actions. Moreover, since the purification of the heart, which is the fruit of daily obligatory and occasional actions, is desired by everyone, abandoning those actions is not proper.",
    
    "vallabh": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Vallabhacharya 18.2 Although Sannyasa and Tyaga have the same basic meaning, Sri Bhagavan Himself spoke the following reply in order to show the decision based on different subjects by presenting alternative views, in the verse beginning with 'kamyanam karmanam'. Sages (yogis) understand Sannyasa to be the physical abandonment of all desire-prompted actions ordained by the Vedas with desire-associated injunctions, such as 'he who desires heaven should perform the Jyotishtoma sacrifice,' 'he crosses over all sins, he crosses over the sin of killing a Brahmana who performs the Ashvamedha sacrifice,' and 'he who desires a son should perform sacrifice.' More discerning and skilled devotees, who do not favor physical abandonment, say that in the scriptures of liberation, the meaning of the word Tyaga is the abandonment of the fruits of all actions—namely the daily obligatory, occasional, and desire-prompted actions, as well as those mentioned in the scriptures—meaning the abandonment of the declared fruit of those actions. Thus, in their view, the meaning of Sannyasa is properly the abandonment of fruits, and not physical abandonment.",
    
    "ms": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Madhusudan Saraswati 18.2 To refute the last of these views, using the needle-and-cauldron maxim (suchi-kataha-nyaya), Sri Bhagavan spoke the reply: 'kamyanam...' Some poets, i.e., subtle thinkers, understand Sannyasa to be the renunciation (nyasa) or abandonment of desire-motivated (kamya) actions, such as sacrifices of animals and soma, which are enjoined out of desire for rewards and are of no use in purifying the heart. Some hold that, according to the scriptural text: 'The Brahmanas seek to know this Self through the study of the Vedas, through sacrifices, charity, and austerity without attachment,' the duties of a celibate student (indicated by the word 'study of the Vedas'), the duties of a householder (indicated by the words 'sacrifice' and 'charity'), and the duties of a forest-dweller (indicated by 'austerity' and 'fasting') are shown to lead to Self-knowledge through the destruction of sins, which is the result of daily obligatory duties. It cannot be said that this application is useless on the ground that it is already obtained by the text: 'Knowledge arises in a person upon the destruction of sinful deeds'; for, if there were no such application, then even if the daily obligatory duties were performed, knowledge might or might not arise. But when there is a scriptural application, knowledge must certainly arise, and this rule is for the sake of restriction. Therefore, since the daily obligatory duties are applied to knowing or the desire to know, those who desire to know, preceding the purification of the mind and the rise of the desire to know, should perform only the daily obligatory duties with the attitude of offering them to the Lord, and should completely abandon all desire-prompted actions together with their fruits. This is one view.\nAnother view is: 'sarvakarmaphalatyagam prahustyagam vicaksanah' -- Discerning thinkers, i.e., those skilled in reasoning, call Tyaga the abandonment of the specific fruits of all actions, whether desire-prompted or daily obligatory, while performing them for the purification of the mind in connection with the desire to know.\nJust as in the case of the statements 'The sacrificial post is made of Khadira wood' and 'For one who desires strength, he should make the post of Khadira wood', the use of Khadira wood is understood to serve both the sacrifice and the person's goal due to different scriptural authorities (the context of the sacrifice and the fruit-association); similarly, for all actions like the Agnihotra, animal sacrifice, and Soma sacrifice mentioned in the Shatapatha Brahmana, their connection with their respective fruits is established by individual texts, and their connection with the desire to know is established by the general text on sacrifice etc. This is reasonable according to the maxim of 'duality of one thing due to separate association' ( संयोगपृथक्त्व न्याय). So it is said in the Samkshepa-shariraka: 'The scriptural sentence beginning with \"through sacrifice\" takes the entire group of actions enjoined in the Shatapatha Brahmana, which are established by their own originative injunctions, and connects them with the single goal of generating the desire to know in a person.' Therefore, even desire-prompted actions should be performed without attachment to their fruits for the purification of the mind. Indeed, there is no inherent distinction like 'desire-prompted' or 'daily obligatory' in actions like the Agnihotra; the distinction is created only by the difference in the performer's intention. When the attachment to fruits is abandoned, how can there be a distinction? And the existence of specific fruits for daily obligatory duties will be shown by the Lord in the verse: 'Threefold is the fruit of action -- undesirable, desirable, and mixed -- which accrues after death to those who do not renounce...' (Gita 18.12).\nThe first half of the verse means the physical abandonment of desire-prompted actions along with their fruits, while performing daily obligatory duties for the sake of generating the desire to know. The second half means that since all actions, whether desire-prompted or daily obligatory, are connected with the desire to know due to separate association, even if they are physically performed for that purpose, one only abandons the attachment to their individual fruits. This is what the author of the Vartika (Sureshvaracharya) says: 'The injunction for daily obligatory duties is taught by the text \"through study of the Vedas...\" for the rise of the knowledge of the oneness of the Self. Or, all actions are for the sake of generating the desire to know, because of the separate association established by the text \"through study of the Vedas...\"'\nThus, the word Sannyasa means the renunciation of desire-prompted actions with their fruits, and the word Tyaga means the abandonment of attachment to the fruits of all actions. Therefore, these two words do not denote entirely different categories like 'pot' and 'cloth'; rather, both have the single meaning of abandoning attachment to fruits while performing actions for the purification of the mind. Thus, this single question of Arjuna has been decided.",
    
    "srid": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Sridhara Swami 18.2 Sri Bhagavan spoke the reply: 'kamyanam...' Sages understand Sannyasa to be the renunciation (nyasa), i.e., giving up, of desire-prompted (kamya) actions enjoined with desire-associated injunctions, such as 'he who desires a son should perform sacrifice' or 'he who desires heaven should perform sacrifice.' The meaning is that scholars know Sannyasa to be the complete renunciation of all actions along with their fruits. Skilled and expert thinkers call the abandonment of only the fruits of all actions—whether desire-prompted, daily obligatory, or occasional—as Tyaga, and not the physical abandonment of actions.\nObjection: Since no fruits are heard of for daily obligatory and occasional duties, how can there be abandonment of a non-existent fruit? Indeed, the abandonment of a barren woman's son is not possible.\nAnswer: Although no specific fruit is heard of in injunctions like 'one should perform the Sandhya worship daily' or 'one should perform the Agnihotra sacrifice as long as one lives'—unlike 'desirous of heaven' or 'desirous of cattle'—yet, a scriptural injunction, being unable to prompt a rational person to a useless activity, must imply some general fruit, just as in the case of 'one should perform the Vishvajit sacrifice.' It should not be thought, as in the Guru's (Prabhakara's) view, that the only purpose of the injunction is the accomplishment of the duty itself through faith, because it is difficult to explain a person's inclination to act without a goal. Moreover, fruits are indeed heard of even for obligatory duties in texts like: 'All these obtain holy worlds,' 'By action, the world of the ancestors is won,' and 'By righteousness, one dispels sin.' Therefore, it is appropriate to say: 'The wise call the abandonment of the fruits of all actions as Tyaga.'\nObjection: By the abandonment of fruits, there would again be non-inclination towards fruitless actions.\nAnswer: No, because all actions are applied for generating the desire to know through separate association. Thus says the Sruti: 'The Brahmanas seek to know this Self through the study of the Vedas, through sacrifices, charity, and austerity without attachment.' Therefore, abandoning all specific fruits as causing bondage, the performance of all actions for the sake of generating the desire to know is indeed proper. And the desire to know is the inward turning of the intellect, characterized by the cessation of identification with the body through the discrimination between the eternal and the transient. Until then, for a person performing the necessary duties conducive to knowledge for the purification of the mind, the abandonment of their fruits alone is called the abandonment of action, and not physical abandonment. Thus says the Sruti: 'Only performing actions here, one should desire to live a hundred years.' After that, the cessation of all actions happens naturally. It is said in the Naishkarmya-siddhi: 'The actions, having generated the inward turning of the intellect through purification, disappear upon achieving their purpose, like clouds at the end of the rainy season.' And it is said by the Lord: 'But the man who rejoices in the Self alone, is satisfied with the Self, and is content in the Self alone, for him there is no duty to perform' (Gita 3.17). And it is said by Vasistha: 'A yogi does not abandon actions; rather, he is abandoned by actions, due to the destruction of the very resolve (sankalpa) which is the root of action.' Or he may abandon them seeing them as obstacles to steadfastness in knowledge. Thus it is said by Sri Bhagavan in the Bhagavata: 'One should perform actions only as long as one has not become detached, or as long as faith in hearing My stories and the like has not arisen. One who is steadfast in knowledge, detached, or My devotee without desires, should abandon the ashramas along with their symbols and wander beyond the scope of scriptural injunctions.' Enough of this elaboration. Let us return to the subject.",
    
    "dhan": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Dhanpati 18.2 Having been asked thus, and understanding Arjuna's intent—that the words Sannyasa and Tyaga mentioned in various places throughout all the chapters do not have clearly distinguished meanings—and considering the question to be proper, Sri Bhagavan spoke for the sake of that decision. Some poets, i.e. scholars, understand Sannyasa, which is the meaning of the word Sannyasa, to be the renunciation (nyasa) or abandonment of desire-prompted actions like the Ashvamedha performed out of desire for heaven and the like, which means the non-performance of those actions that present themselves as duties. Expert and skilled scholars call the abandonment of the fruits accruing to oneself from all actions, including the daily obligatory and occasional ones that are performed, as Tyaga, which is the meaning of the word Tyaga.\nObjection: Since the daily obligatory and occasional duties have no fruits, it is impossible to abandon their fruits—just like abandoning the son of a barren woman. Therefore, the stated meaning of Tyaga is not proper.\nAnswer: Although no specific fruit is heard of in injunctions like 'one should perform the Sandhya worship' or 'one should perform the Agnihotra sacrifice as long as one lives'—unlike 'desirous of heaven' or 'desirous of cattle'—yet, a scriptural injunction, being unable to prompt a rational person to a useless activity, must imply some fruit, according to the Vishvajit maxim. Moreover, fruits are indeed heard of for obligatory duties in texts like: 'All these obtain holy worlds,' 'By action, the world of the ancestors is won,' and 'By righteousness, one dispels sin.' And the Lord will say: 'Threefold is the fruit of action -- undesirable, desirable, and mixed -- which accrues after death to those who do not renounce, but never to those who renounce' (Gita 18.12). Therefore, it is appropriate to say: 'The wise call the abandonment of the fruits of all actions as Tyaga.'\nObjection: Even so, there would be non-inclination towards fruitless actions.\nAnswer: No, because all actions are applied for generating the desire to know through separate association, according to the Sruti: 'The Brahmanas seek to know this Self through the study of the Vedas, through sacrifices, charity, and austerity without attachment.' This is what Sureshvaracharya says: 'The injunction for daily obligatory duties is taught by the text \"through study of the Vedas...\" for the rise of the knowledge of the oneness of the Self. Or, all actions are for the sake of generating the desire to know, because of the separate association established by the text \"through study of the Vedas...\"' And the aphorism in the fourth chapter of Purva Mimamsa says: 'One and the same thing can serve both purposes due to separate association' (एकस्य तूभयत्वं संयोगपृथक्त्वम्). For example, in the statements 'The sacrificial post is made of Khadira wood' and 'For one who desires strength, he should make the post of Khadira wood', the single fact of being Khadira wood serves both the sacrifice and the person's goal, and there is no contradiction because the connection of being subordinate to the sacrifice and subordinate to the fruit is understood through two different texts. Similarly, for all actions established by their own originative injunctions, their connection with their respective fruits is established by individual texts, and their connection with the desire to know is established by the text 'through study of the Vedas...'",
    
    "venkat": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Vedantadeshikacharya Venkatanatha 18.2 If the question is due to a desire to know their difference, unity, or their true nature, then in which part is the presentation of different views like 'kamyanam...' appropriate? To this, [the commentator] says 'atha...' (now...). The intention is: Here, the decision is established through reasoning; and reasoning is introduced when there is doubt. The doubt here is caused by the disagreement among disputants, so the different views are presented to clarify the subject of reasoning. By this, it is also indicated that the question is asked again in this chapter to resolve the disagreement regarding the words Sannyasa and Tyaga, even though their meanings have already been spoken. Since the reply by accepting their unity logically rejects their difference, [the commentator] says 'ekam eva svarupam...' (only one nature). This is because the Lord will state His own view in 'Hear My decision...' (Gita 18.4).\nThe two words 'kavayah' (sages) and 'vicaksanah' (the wise) do not refer to the superiority of the speakers or the excellence of meaning, but rather to the mere knowledge suitable for understanding the disagreement; hence [the commentator] says 'some scholars.' Since the next verse clearly states the division by the words 'some' and 'others', the same intention is implied here; hence 'some' is said.\nBy the qualification 'renunciation of desire-prompted actions,' the non-renunciation of others is implied; and in the subsequent text, by the qualification 'abandonment of the fruits of all actions,' the physical abandonment of desire-prompted actions is implied here; hence [the commentator] says 'physical abandonment.'\nThe intention of those who advocate the physical abandonment of desire-prompted actions is: Unlike the daily obligatory and occasional duties, desire-prompted actions are not performed out of fear of sin due to non-performance or unfit condition for other actions. Nor are they performed for the sake of the three goals of life (dharma, artha, kama), because they are contrary to liberation. Nor can that same action be the direct means to liberation, as that would render meditation and other practices useless. Nor are they accepted as parts of knowledge due to separate application, because there is no contradiction in the text on sacrifice etc. referring only to daily obligatory and occasional duties. Indeed, the aphorism 'And there is need of all works, on account of the scriptural statement of sacrifices, etc., as in the case of a horse' (Brahma Sutra 3.4.26) is explained as referring to dependence on the duties of the stages of life. Therefore, desire-prompted actions, which lead to heaven and other hell-like states, should not be performed by seekers of liberation.\n\nThe intention of those who advocate 'abandonment of the fruits of all actions' is: Since the opposition of fruits is the reason for doubting desire-prompted actions, let the fruits alone be abandoned; there is no occasion for useless performance, because their performance is justified as being solely for the pleasure of the Lord, just like daily obligatory and occasional duties. Nor is there a lack of injunction in this, because texts like: 'He who departs from this world, O Gargi, without knowing this Imperishable, and performs sacrifices, offers oblations, and practices austerities for many thousands of years, his work indeed has an end' (Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.8.10) show that the same action leads to transient or eternal fruits based on the knowledge or ignorance of the Supreme Person indicated by the word 'Imperishable'. Therefore, like the daily obligatory and occasional duties, desire-prompted actions also do not require physical abandonment.\n\nSince the dispute cannot relate to different subjects, and since the words Tyaga and Sannyasa must have the same meaning here, the rejection of the doubt regarding their different meanings is logically obtained; hence [the commentator] says 'tatra...' (there...). By this, those who say that one word refers to the physical abandonment of desire-prompted actions and the other refers to the disregard of the fruits of daily obligatory and occasional duties are refuted. Indeed, it is not said here 'abandoning the fruits of actions other than desire-prompted ones.' Consequently, due to the absence of any limiting factor, all three types of actions are included. This is what is meant by 'the daily obligatory, occasional, and desire-prompted actions.' Even for daily obligatory duties, the connection with fruits is understood from texts like: 'The Prajapatya region is for householders' (Vishnu Purana 1.6.37).\n\nTo refute the view that this verse is intended to establish different meanings for the words Tyaga and Sannyasa, [the commentator] states two clear reasons for their having the same meaning: 'tatha...' (similarly...). Indeed, in a discussion concerning two different meanings, a decision on only one of them would not be proper; hence it is said 'by the word Tyaga alone.'\n'And from the appearance of mutual synonymy' -- the intention is: Sannyasa is prohibited in 'But the renunciation (Sannyasa) of obligatory work is not proper' (Gita 18.7). Having repeated it by the word Tyaga in 'Abandonment (Tyaga) of it through delusion is declared to be Tamasika' (Gita 18.7), it is condemned as Tamasika; otherwise, there would be a lack of connection between them, like sentences about an old bull etc. Similarly, the statement 'accrue after death to those who do not resort to Tyaga' (Gita 18.12) is strengthened by the contrast 'but never to those who resort to Sannyasa' (Gita 18.12). And the contrast of one is not the absence of another. Therefore, it is accepted that these two words have the same meaning here; 'by the Respondent (Sri Bhagavan)' is the remaining sense.",
    
    "puru": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Purushottamji 18.2 Sri Bhagavan spoke the reply to this: 'kamyanam...' Sages (kavayah), i.e., those who delight in faultless words, understand Sannyasa to be the renunciation (nyasa) or abandonment of desire-prompted actions, such as those mentioned in injunctions like: 'desirous of heaven, one should perform the Jyotishtoma sacrifice,' and 'he who performs the Ashvamedha sacrifice crosses over all sins, crosses over the sin of killing a Brahmana.' The intention here is: by the word Sannyasa, which means proper placing or offering, they know through the knowledge of word-meanings that it means offering the fruits of desire-prompted actions for the sake of the Lord by abandoning the desired fruits. By this, it is only said that they possess knowledge of the literal meaning of words, but not the knowledge of the ultimate truth (tattva-jnana). Furthermore, those who are wise (vicaksanah), i.e., particularly capable of explanation and endowed with cleverness, call the abandonment of the fruits of all actions, including the daily obligatory and occasional ones, as Tyaga. Although no fruit is heard of in daily obligatory duties like 'one should perform the Sandhya worship daily' and 'one should perform the Agnihotra sacrifice as long as one lives,' they assume that the avoidance of sin (pratyavaya-parihara) is the fruit. This is what is meant by their being 'wise'. The implication is that they too do not know the ultimate truth.",
    
    "neel": "Sanskrit Commentary By Sri Neelkanth 18.2 Sri Bhagavan spoke the reply here: 'kamyanam...' Anticipating the objection: 'Since desire-prompted actions like the sacrifice for obtaining a son are performed out of attachment, and since the fruit is the object of desire, and because all actions are rule-bound to yield fruits, all action is indeed desire-prompted. Therefore, a seeker of liberation must abandon daily obligatory duties as well, which is our desired conclusion' -- to this [the Lord] says 'sarva...' The wise call the abandonment of the fruits of all actions—daily obligatory, occasional, and desire-prompted—as Tyaga, and they do not advocate physical abandonment. The meaning is: therefore, Sannyasa as desired by you cannot be established.\nThe intention is: although both the words Sannyasa and Tyaga speak of cessation, yet that cessation arises either from dispassion, fear of physical pain, or delusion. Since its causes vary as Sattvika etc., its threefold division as Sattvika, Rajasa, and Tamasa, and the predominance of the three types of faith, are unavoidable. Moreover, a person who is not detached and lacks faith, even if he has abandoned actions, is seen to be not free from visible distraction. As said by the author of the Vartika (Sureshvaracharya): 'Monks who are negligent, outward-minded, slanderers, and eager to quarrel are also seen, their minds being corrupted by fate.' Therefore, keeping in mind that the performance of desireless actions is better than Sannyasa performed by one who is not detached, the Lord praises the renunciation of desire-prompted actions as Sannyasa, and the non-seeking of the fruits of daily obligatory and other actions as Tyaga. Therefore, Sannyasa performed without faith is indeed non-existent, and it cannot yield its fruit, which is remembered as the state of Brahman; hence the Lord has rightly said that everything done without faith is useless.\nAs for the explanation: 'the first half of the verse means the physical abandonment of desire-prompted actions, because only daily obligatory duties are connected with the desire to know; the second half means the abandonment of fruits of all actions,' which is intended to show two views, it is disregarded because it leads to repetition with the next verse."
}

